    "content": "Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed told delegates at the National Dialogue Forum in Addis Ababa on Wednesday that Ethiopia's loss of direct access to the Red Sea stems from internal political divisions rather than external coercion. Speaking to over 4,000 attendees, he described the country as a 'geographic prisoner' of its own making.\n\nThe forum, aimed at fostering national consensus, provided a platform for Mr. Abiy to reiterate his administration's stance that past governments failed to manage internal differences effectively. He argued that these divisions allowed external actors to exploit the situation, undermining Ethiopia's strategic interests.\n\nThis statement is part of a broader narrative from the current government, which has long asserted that historical mistakes—not international agreements or military defeats—are responsible for Ethiopia's landlocked status after Eritrea's independence in 1993. The issue remains a sensitive one in Ethiopian politics.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, the Red Sea access debate holds particular significance. Somalia and Ethiopia have had strained relations over territorial and maritime issues, including the port of Berbera and the construction of the Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam. Any shift in Ethiopia's strategic posture could affect regional stability and trade routes vital to the Horn of Africa.\n\nThe National Dialogue Forum is expected to continue discussions on national unity, with the Red Sea issue likely to remain a contentious topic amid ongoing tensions with neighboring countries.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/16/we-lost-it-ourselves-abiy-admits-internal-flaws-cost-ethiopia-red-sea/?utm_source=rss&#038;utm_medium=rss&#038;utm_campaign=we-lost-it-ourselves-abiy-admits-internal-flaws-cost-ethiopia-red-sea",
