    "slug": "new-customs-fees-at-bossaso-port-stall-trade-spark-friction-with-local-traders",
    "summary": "A sudden increase in customs service fees at Bossaso port in Puntland has disrupted commercial activity, with traders protesting the new charges and warning of economic slowdown.",
    "content": "Commercial operations at the Bossaso port in Puntland’s Bari region have come to a near standstill following the introduction of increased customs service fees. The new charges, which were implemented without prior consultation with business owners, have prompted widespread complaints from local traders who report that containers are being held up and imports are declining.\n\nThe fee hike was announced by the Puntland customs authority in early April, raising levies on a range of goods entering through the port. Traders argue that the increases are arbitrary and come at a time when the local economy is already struggling due to high inflation and reduced purchasing power. The Bossaso port is one of the region’s main economic gateways, handling the majority of imports for Puntland and neighboring areas.\n\nThis dispute is not the first between the Puntland government and the business community over port fees. In 2021, similar protests led to temporary concessions from authorities. However, this time the situation appears more tense, with some traders threatening to redirect shipments to alternative ports in Somaliland or overseas, which could further weaken Puntland’s revenue base.\n\nThe impact of the standoff extends to the Somali diaspora in places like Minneapolis, Toronto, and London, who rely on the port to send remittances and goods to relatives in Puntland. Delays and higher costs at Bossaso ultimately reduce the value of remittance flows, which are a critical source of income for many families.\n\nLocal officials have yet to publicly respond to the traders’ grievances, but sources indicate that mediation efforts are underway. The Puntland Chamber of Commerce has called for an immediate suspension of the new fees pending dialogue. Without a resolution, the prolonged disruption risks raising commodity prices across the region and stifling the small businesses that anchor the local economy.\n\nRead the original report from Horseed Media here: https://horseedmedia.net/wararkii-ugu-dambeeyey-ee-muranka-ka-dhashay-khidmadaha-lagu-soo-rogey-dekedda-boosaaso/423755/",
